lzh_formatted:
  title: 李敎授
  author: 曺偉
  language: lzh
  text: 龍灣學舍南城隅。函丈先生淸且臞。纚纚腹有五經笥。口誦詩書如貫珠。捫虱時時卧塵榻。發篋探囊逢惡客。明年科第如摘髭。賈勇文塲奮鼓角。優游餘事精弈棋。虎穴得子人稱奇。彦道呼盧那可數。積薪妙術誰得知。濮陽公子長九尺。奮髯大叫亦勁敵。一戰雖捷黑牧丹。再戰不支摧兩翼。一勝一負眞乘除。責辦一席在須臾。諸生貿貿執刀匕。侍兒婉婉羅酒壺。南堂閑敞宜望遠。習習東風吹柳線。燒痕春雪未全融。眼底雲山繞海甸。滿座高談皆楚囚。一歡傾倒消百憂。就中更有紅蓮客。一笑破的降龜州。龜州擧觶屢稱屈。罰籌如蝟潛走逸。歸來街鼓已逄逄。不覺城頭鴉尾畢。人生到處如萍蓬。豈料天涯有今日。南堂之會不可忘。恨我苦乏如椽筆。濮陽。指吳龜城自瑩。紅蓮客。評事尹世霖也。
korean:
  title: 남당에 가서 이 교수
  author: 조위
  language: kor
  text: |-
    용만(의주) 학사 남성 구석에
    함장 선생이 맑고 또 여윈 얼굴
    뱃속엔 차곡차곡 오경을 간직했고
    입으론 구슬 꿰듯 시서를 외네
    이따금 이 잡으며 진탑에 누웠느라면
    도둑이 농 헤치고 주머니도 뒤지네
    명년의 과거는 따고 난 당상
    글 짓는 마당에는 용맹을 과시
    놀이의 여사론 바둑 잘 두어
    범의 굴에 새끼 잡으니 사람들 탄복
    언도의 호로(투전ㆍ골패 따위) 어찌 대수로우리
    ‘적신’의 묘술을 누가 알 것인가
    복양공자는 키가 아홉 자
    수염 뻗치고 대드니 제 또한 강적
    첫싸움에 흑모란을 이기었으나
    둘째 쌈에 못 부지해 날개 꺾였네
    한 번 이기고 한 번 지니 무승부로군
    내기 턱은 금방 내얄 수밖에
    제생들이 분분히 칼ㆍ수저 들고
    시동들이 오순도순 술병 차리네
    남당이 헌칠하여 조망이 좋고
    동풍이 설렁설렁 버들가지를 부는데
    화전의 봄눈이 아직 다 안 녹았고
    바닷가의 운산이 눈 아래 구불구불
    만좌의 고담이 모두 다 초수
    좋아하고 떠들며 근심을 잊네
    그 중엔 홍련객(막부(幕府)의 서기)이 한 분 있어서
    한 번 웃고 과녁 맞춰 귀주를 항복케 하니
    귀주가 술잔 들며 연속 졌다 하다가
    집중되는 벌주에 그만 줄행랑
    돌아오니 거리의 북 소리가 땅땅
    성 머리에 해가 지는 것도 몰랐네
    인생은 도처에 부평초와 같거니
    천애에 오늘이 있을 줄을 알았으리
    남당의 모임을 잊을 수 없으나
    내게 서까래만한 붓이 없으니 어쩌리
    복양(濮陽)은 오귀성(吳龜城) 자영(自瑩)을 가리킴이요, 홍련객(紅蓮客)은 평사(評事)  윤세림(尹世霖)이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1410_010_0340&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: At the Southern Hall, to Professor Yi
  author: Jo Wei
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the southern corner of Yongman's school in Uiju,
    There dwells Master Ham, spare and radiant,
    His belly holds the Five Classics stacked like treasures,
    From his lips flow the Odes and Books like strung pearls.

    Often he lies on dusty mats, hunting lice,
    While thieves ransack chests and rifle through pockets—
    Yet next year's examination, he'll pluck like whiskers from the chin,
    And display his valor in the field of letters with drums and horns.

    In idle pursuits he excels at the game of stones,
    Capturing tiger cubs in their lair—men marvel at such skill.
    Who counts Yan Dao's casting lots a trifle?
    Who knows the subtle art of piling fortunes high?

    The master of Puyang, nine feet tall,
    Strokes his whiskers and roars—a worthy opponent indeed!
    First battle: black peonies fall before him,
    Second battle: he cannot hold—both wings collapse.
    One victory, one defeat—true mathematics of gain and loss.
    The stakes settled in but a moment's time.

    Students bustle about with knives and spoons,
    Attendants arrange wine vessels with graceful care.
    The Southern Hall opens wide, perfect for distant views,
    East wind gently brushes the willow threads,
    Spring snow on burnt earth not yet fully melted,
    Clouds and mountains wind around the seaside plain.

    The hall fills with lofty talk, all prisoners of Chu,
    One joy, one laughter sweeps away a hundred griefs.
    Among them sits the Red Lotus Guest,
    One smile finds the mark—tames the Turtle Isle to submission!

    Turtle Isle raises his cup, crying defeat repeatedly,
    Forfeit tokens multiply like hedgehog spines, then scatter in flight.
    Returning home, street drums beat rhythmically on,
    Unaware the crows have finished their perch at the city gate.

    Life everywhere is drifting duckweed,
    How could we have known this day would come at world's end?
    The gathering at Southern Hall—I cannot forget,
    Yet alas, I lack a brush as thick as rafters to record it.
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''Five Classics'' (五經) refers to the foundational texts of Confucian learning: the Classic of Poetry, Book of History, Book of Rites, Spring and Autumn Annals, and the Book of Changes.'
    - Yongman (用漫) refers to Uiju, a city in northern Korea known for its schools.
    - '''Prisoners of Chu'' is an idiom suggesting eloquent or elevated speech.'
    - The Red Lotus Guest and Turtle Isle are references to specific individuals present at this gathering, their wit and competitive spirit celebrated through witty wordplay.
